conclusion: Theory of psychoanalysis has changed considerably, moving away from childhood trauma as the sole cause of neuroses.
Traumatic theory is insufficient for explaining hysteria because of the complexity of neuroses and the role of predisposition and environment.
Repression is the psychic mechanism that moves conscious thoughts into the unconscious, forming the basis for neurotic symptoms.
Freud gave up the notion that sexual trauma in childhood is the direct cause of neuroses; phantasy can have equivalent traumatic value.
Neurosis requires an internal predisposition that interacts with trauma; otherwise trauma leaves no lasting mark.
Children possess a highly developed, polymorphic-perverse sexuality that Freud identified through exhaustive investigation.
Sexuality is the instinct for the preservation of the species, extending beyond genital functions to include psychological phenomena from early childhood.
Infantile sexuality is auto-erotic and directed at various erogenous zones rather than specifically genital or heterosexual.
Libido is a dynamic psychological energy that accounts for the shifting of sexual manifestations, replacing fixed components with a unified energic concept.
Human life is divided into pre-sexual (infancy), pre-pubertal (childhood), and mature (post-pubertal) phases, with sexuality developing gradually from nutritional functions.
Infantile sexual inclinations must be relinquished for normal development; persistence leads to perverse states.
Neurosis results from libido becoming fixed at pre-sexual stages.
Traumatic events do not cause neurosis; the key factor is retardation of infantile development.
Neurosis arises from retardation in emotional development, producing infantile phantasies.
Introversion occurs when libido is directed inward rather than toward external adaptation.
The images of parents provide a field for introverted libido, shaping neurotic behavior.
Unconscious phantasies are central to the etiology of neurosis and are the object of psychoanalytic investigation.
Dreams are products of unconscious origin built from past reminiscences.
The Å’dipus-complex is an infantile phantasy involving desire for one parent and rivalry with the other.
Neurosis arises when libido regresses to infantile stages because of current conflicts, creating an apparent past etiology.
Neurosis is a symptom of a discord within the self, a struggle between two divergent tendencies.
Critical sensitiveness is innate and becomes manifest in unusual situations.
Regression is a key factor in the emotional development of highly sensitive individuals.
Neurosis is a reaction to an actual conflict, not merely rooted in childhood.
Phantasies serve as compensations for unfulfilled adaptations to reality.
Psychoanalysis grants regressive phantasies so that libido can be understood and redirected.
Transference occurs when libido and phantasies are directed toward the physician.
Analyzing transference liberates the patient from unconscious dependency on the analyst.
Psychoanalysts must undergo psychoanalysis to eliminate unconscious interferences in their work.
Dreams have a prospective (teleological) function in preparing future life tendencies.
Psychoanalysis is superior to suggestion therapies as it addresses root causes rather than symptoms.
Psychoanalysis deals with knowledge and its formulations, not faith, allowing for ongoing evolution.
Psychoanalytic insights can inform pedagogy by understanding infantile development.
Critics often attack psychoanalysis out of ignorance or prejudice, ignoring its scientific basis.
Theories are instruments for work, not final answers, allowing for change based on experience.
Psychoanalysis provides a meta-framework for understanding psychological phenomena beyond specific theories.
Jung's work builds on Freud's, with modest criticism to advance the field, not create schism.
